### Motorn’s Neuroma

- What is it? What nerve involved?
    - It is the compressive neuropathy of the common plantar **interdigital nerve**
    - **Not a true neuroma.**
- What is the interdigital nerve?
    - Interdigital nerve = confluence branches of **lateral and medial plantar nerves**

- ‼️ What is the histology?
    - **Perineurial fibrosis**, degeneration of nerve fibres
- Clinical finding?
    - Mulder’s click - squeeze forefoot while palpating webspace to feel flick
- Investigation?
    - MRI
- What is non op management?
    - Wide shoe box, steroid injection
- How effective is H and L injection?
    - H and L injection - Markovic et al. 2008 FAI journal - 38% completely resolve after steroid injection.
        - 39 injections under US guidance
        - 66% positive outcomes. (38% complete satisfaction, 28% satisfied)

### Freiberg’s Disease

![Untitled](Tarsal%20Tunnel%20Syndrome%20Morton%E2%80%99s%20Freiberg%E2%80%99s%20Disease%2016995645b378444c9285ae0ecad13748/Untitled%204.png)

- What is Freiberg?
    - Rare foot condition Characterised by infarction and fracture of the MT head
- Which toes most common?
    - 2nd MT - due to longer MT
    - 4th and 5th rarely affected
- Classification of Freiberg?
    - **Smillie** Classification
        - Stage 1 = subchondral fracture only on MRI
        - 2 = **dorsal** collapse of **articular surface only**
        - 3 = collapse of **dorsal** MT head; plantar portion intact
        - 4 = collapse of **whole** MT head
        - 5 = **Arthritic** changes

- Management of Freiberg?
    - Non op - air cast boot, stiff soled shoe
    - Op (rarely required)
        - Joint preserving
            - MTPJ arthrotomy with removal of loose bodies
            - Dorsal closing wedge osteotomy (to off load dorsal forces in stage 2/3)
        - Joint sacrificing
            - DuVries Arthroplasty (excision arthroplasty)
